Marine Library Development Phase
(Control – Similarity – Scaffold and Pharmacophore Mapping – AI-De Novo Generation)
(1) Marine Control Identification: We extract marine control from two different databases, where FDA-originated controls were extracted from the PubChem, and pure marine natural compounds were extracted from the CMNPD.

i. PubChem: Vidarabine and Remdesivir
ii. CMNPD: Aureol, Homofascaplysin-A, Dieckol, Gracilin-A, Stypoldione, Bromophycolide-A, Barettin, and Lamellarin-H

(2) Similarity-Based: From these two types of controls, we expand our marine-inspired chemical library using several similarity methods. Compounds were collected as multi-SDF (3D) and CSV (SMILES and ID) file formats from the Public database.

i. PubChem Similarity Tanimoto (FDA-approved reference controls 97%):   Rather than treating a molecule as a simple string of text, this method converts FDA-approved reference controls (vidarabine, remdesivir) into a 2D chemical graph where atoms represent vertices and covalent bonds represent edges. The method uses two distinct components to execute your 97% expansion:

The Fingerprint Engine (PUBCHEM_CACTVS_SUBGRAPHKEYS): 
PubChem's native CACTVS system assigns an 881-bit binary vector (a string of 881 zeros and ones) to each compound. Each bit represents an absolute structural fragment, an atom type, a ring configuration, or a coordination neighborhood. If a molecule contains a specific fragment (eg, a purine ring backbone or an adenosine-like core), that specific bit flips from 0 to 1.

The Similarity Metric (Tanimoto Coefficient, Tc): 
The script compares the 881-bit vector of your reference drug (A) against millions of candidate vectors in the PubChem database (B) using a bitwise intersection-over-union metric. A threshold of 97% (Tc 0.97) represents a strict near-isomeric filter, forcing the system to isolate compounds where at least 854 out of the 881 structural fragment keys match perfectly.



In the second phase of our study, a multi-tiered structural similarity search was conducted to expand the initial control set into a comprehensive screening library. For the clinically validated controls, structural analogs of four FDA-approved antiviral controls (Vidarabine, Remdesivir) were retrieved using a custom Python-based script executed in the Google Colab environment. This interface used the PubChem PUG-REST API to access the PUBCHEM_CACTVS_SUBGRAPHKEYS algorithm, an 881-bit substructure-based fingerprinting method. A rigorous Tanimoto coefficient (Tc) threshold of 97% was applied to identify near-isomeric clusters and highly conserved pharmacophoric features. 

