(3) Scaffold Hopping and Pharmacophore Mapping
The script executes a Three-Tiered Structure-Based Ligand Alignment Funnel driven by the following four core scientific methods:
I.	2D Topological Path-Graph Filtering (The Dissimilarity Gate)
The script calculates topological path fingerprints using RDKit's graph-theory architecture and compares them using the Tanimoto Coefficient (Tc). By enforcing a strict ceiling boundary (Tc 0.42), the method filters out traditional structural clones and close chemical analogs. This mathematically guarantees a true "scaffold hop" - meaning the core ring connectivity is fundamentally rearranged while maintaining the potential for similar 3D spatial properties.

II.	Knowledge-Based Distance Geometry Conformation Ensemble Sampling (ETKDGv3) 
To sample the structural flexibility of bioactive natural product and drug candidates, the Experimental-Torsion Knowledge-Distance Geometry (ETKDG) model was used here. This approach generates 3D coordinate sets by combining classical distance-bound matrix geometry with experimental torsion-angle preferences extracted from thousands of high-resolution structures in the Cambridge Structural Database (CSD) and the Protein Data Bank (PDB). The updated v3 parameters include specialized optimizations for macrocyclic ring boundaries and heavily strained heterocycles that are essential for complex molecules.

III.	Cartesian 3D Grid Volume Intersection Mapping (Shape Similarity)
Spatial volume overlaps are evaluated using a non-parametric grid-intersection model. Both the reference control and the candidate conformer are enveloped in a dense 3D Cartesian voxel grid. The software calculates the hard geometric overlap of the atomic coordinate volumes to yield a Shape Tanimoto Distance (STD). This provides an unbiased measure of global 3D shape congruence that is completely independent of the underlying 2D chemical formula. 

IV.	Isotropic 3D Pharmacophore Feature Distance Constrained Matrix (MESP Field Approximation)
The phenomenon of molecular recognition by identifying structural functional features (Hydrogen Bond Donors, Acceptors, and Positively Ionizable Groups), independent of atom types. The software maps these features as 3D coordinate vectors. It loops through the conformer ensemble and computes a Euclidean Distance Matrix (EDM) between the candidate's features and the control anchor's nodes. Any pair sharing the same chemical feature within a strict 2.0 AA spatial radius triggers a hit, which is weighted by a Weighted Index to prioritize highly directional hydrogen-bonding regions over peripheral hydrophobic contacts.

