(4) AI-Driven De Novo Generation: This script deploys three core methodologies widely validated in Computer-Aided Drug Design (CADD) for fragment-based de novo design. 
i.	The BRICS Fragmentation and Combinatorial Synthesis Model
Your code uses BRICS Decompose and BRICSBuild. BRICS (Bccr Rules for Combinatorial Chemistry Synthesis) is a fragment-based design model that breaks down molecules into 16 specific, structurally stable bond environments (such as peptides, alkyl-aryl linkages, and ethers) and matches them to real-world organic reactions. The algorithm catalogs these fragments by their cleavage environments and reassembles them combinatorially into unique structural arrangements. This ensures that the generated molecules are not just wild computational guesses but are synthetically feasible in a wet lab. 

ii.	Distance Geometry Conformation Sampling: The ETKDG Method
Your code specifies AllChem.ETKDGv3(). When the script converts a flat 2D SMILES string into a 3D structural model, it uses the Experimental-Torsion Knowledge-Distance Geometry (ETKDG) method. This model combines classical, distance-bound geometry algorithms with structural torsion angle preferences extracted directly from the Cambridge Structural Database (CSD) and the Protein Data Bank (PDB). Version 3 includes specialized parameter optimizations for macrocyclic networks and highly constrained ring frameworks. 

iii.	Cartesian 3D Grid Volume Intersection Mapping
The code tracks rdShapeHelpers.ShapeTanimotoDist (c_mol, new_mol). This method evaluates spatial overlap by placing both molecules in a dense 3D grid. It calculates the volume of intersection of their atomic coordinates to compute a Shape Tanimoto Coefficient. This measures pure 3D shape alignment on a scale from 0.0 to 1.0, completely independent of 2D chemical formula elements. 

